@node intro "Introduction.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Intro
  ~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   This program enables you to use all possible keys on your keyboard
   and the extra mouse buttons. This means that you can use the multimedia
   keys on PC-keyboards such as Play, Stop, Previous, Next, Menu and others.

   FAQ:
   Q. Why should I use AllKeys instead of F-Key on OS4?
   A. Because F-Key is just a commodity and thus cannot read unnamed keys,
      such as most multimedia-keys.
   A. Because AllKeys, using the Eat switch, overrides the screenblanker
      which makes it usable even after the screenblanker has switched off
      the monitor, without switching it on again. This is most useful when
      operating a music player with AllKeys where I'm sure you don't want
      to wake up the monitor just to put the music on pause or change the
      volume.

   Q. Is this program useful to me even if I don't have a multimedia
      keyboard with all those extra buttons?
   A. Yes. You can map the keys Pause/Break, PrtScr/SysRq, Home, End,
      Insert, etc. using this program. Of course you can use it for
      any normal key and key-combination like Shift, Ctrl, LAmiga+g
      and all letters etc. too!
      And you can use the keys without deactivating the screenblanker.
      And you can map mouse buttons and wheels, or mouse button combinations.


@endnode

@node install "Installation.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Installation
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   You can copy the program anywhere in your system you like. If you
   would like to have the program running in the background you can
   add it to WBStartup or add a line like this:
      Run >NIL: AllKeys
   to you user-startup. But first you need to read @{" usage " link usage}.


@endnode

@node req "Requirements.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Requirements
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   This program requires AmigaOS 4.


@endnode

@node usage "Usage.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Usage
  ~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   AllKeys has a configuration GUI that can be accessed from commodities Exchange.
   Here you can add and edit all the keys.

   There are three ways a key can be used:
   1. Can execute a command.
   2. Can send an arexx command to an arexx port.
   3. Can translate a key into another.

   @{fg shine}Keys@{fg text}

     @{b}Code@{ub}
       Shows the key code as a composition of qualifier and rawkey code.

     @{b}Class@{ub}
       There are four supported classes:
       RAWKEY (normal keys)
       XKEY (multimedia-keys)
       MOUSE (mouse buttons)
       WHEEL (the mouse wheel)

       When a key has a subclass other than 1 for XKEY and 0 for other classes
       it will be appened after a slash. XKEYs usually have a subclass showing
       if it is a SET1 (PS/2) or HID (USB) class. PS/2 and USB keyboard present
       totally different codes so if you switch port you need to relearn the
       keys but double-clicking and record the key again.

       Some keys output both RAWKEY and XKEY. PageUp/PageDown are examples
       of that.

     @{b}Explanation@{ub}
       A text line explaining the key, if AllKeys knows the key, otherwise the
       qualifiers and a number will be printed.

     @{b}Translate into@{ub}
       This is used to set another keycode that the Code should be translated
       into. You can for example translate Insert to Help if you have trouble
       using Scroll Lock as Help key. Or why not translate the 4th mouse button
       into LAmiga+m for simple screen switching using the mouse.

       You can however not translate a qualifier to be used as another qualifier.
       Ex: Translate RShift to use as RAmiga for menu hotkeys or something does
       not work. Only the actual key press is translated, not the qualifier code
       when used together with other keys.

       You can translate a code into several other codes. Add one line for each
       translation and they will be processed from the top down in the prefs file.

       The original code will also be sent right before the translated code
       unless Eat or "Eat all configured keys" is used, in that case only the
       translated code will be sent.

       Use the Translate button to record a key or double-click into the translate
       field to type the code by hand if you know it.
       Ex: TRANSLATE=$8001e069,RAWKEY
       Ex: TRANSLATE=$8001e069,XKEY,2

     @{b}ARexx Port@{ub}
       This is the name of the arexx port if you decide to use an arexx command.
       Double-click the field to edit inline.

     @{b}ARexx Command@{ub}
       Specify a simple one-line arexx command. It is about 10 times more efficient
       to use this method instead of executing "rx 'some commandline'". Makes your
       hotkey much more responsive.

       An arexx port is necessary to make this work.

     @{b}Command@{ub}
       This is the CLI command line that should be executed for your key.

       Note that commands are executed synchronously so you probably want to put
       "Run >NIL: " or "WBRun " infront of programs that does not exit immediately
       or they will block AllKeys from processing more keys until the program has
       exited. If you need more arexx functionality than one simple arexx command
       can provide you can of course execute an arexx script here as well using "rx".

       If you like to manipulate windows and screens I recommend using the
       supplied tool ActivateWindow. AllKeys+ActivateWindow replaces ClickTofront,
       toBack&Front and F-Key's window manipulation features plus that you
       get a much greater control over how to configure your hotkeys.


     @{b}Add@{ub}
       Add a new key. An input window will open in which you can see all keys
       being pressed. See further down for a more thorough explanation.

     @{b}Duplicate@{ub}
       Duplicate a key. Useful if you want the same key to send multiple arexx
       commands for example. Like the Stop key to send stop to all your players.

     @{b}Edit@{ub}
       Edit an existing key. The input window will open to let you pick a new key.

     @{b}Translate@{ub}
       Opens the input window for picking a key code to translate an existing code to.

     @{b}Remove@{ub}
       Delete one line.

     @{b}Eat@{ub}
       This switch will make the key become consumed by AllKeys. This gets
       automatically set if the "Eat all configured keys" switch is used.
       Useful if you don't like the key to affect a screenblanker, or any
       other program.

       If you use a key with qualifier that you want to be eaten you need
       also specify the qualifier to be eaten or else it will affect the
       screenblanker or whatever you want to bypass. Specify the qualifier,
       e.g. Shift($80010060), on a line of its own with the Eat switch and
       nothing else. Now you can press Shift+<your key> safely.

     @{b}/\\  \\/@{ub}
       Arrows used to move a line up or down.


   @{fg shine}Settings@{fg text}

     @{b}Priority of the input-handler@{ub}
       This is the priority of the input-handler. It is not a task
       priority. The Console is at pri 0, Intution is at pri 50.
       If you intend to read anything it is adviced to give a higher
       priority than Intuition otherwise intuition will consume most
       key events. Default is priority 70. Highest priority is 127.
  
       Setting the priority higher can be useful if you want the keys
       to be eaten by AllKeys, but you have a screen blanker with a high
       priority which gets the keys before AllKeys has the chance to
       eat them. Blanker in OS4 seems to have a lower pri than 70 and
       the Eat switch can effectively be used to prevent the screen
       blanker from coming off when using eaten hotkeys.
  
     @{b}Eat all configured keys, do not send them further to other programs@{ub}
       If this switch is specified then all keys that are not to be
       translated will be eaten by AllKeys, i.e. not propagated through
       to other handlers. This is useful if you want to be able to use
       your keys without deactivating a screen blanker, or if you simply
       don't want the keys to reach other programs. This switch overrides
       and sets the Eat switch for "the rest of the lines".

     @{b}Ignore the relativemouse qualifier; make keys useful also without a mouse connected@{ub}
       This switch is useful if you sometimes don't have a mouse connected
       to your computer, like e.g. if it is wireless and needs recharging.
       If you boot your computer without a mouse all keys will lack a
       specific flag which will effectively prevent any hotkleys from
       working in many programs, like AllKeys, ToolsDaemon, etc.
  
       Use this switch if you have that problem.

     @{b}Set the relativemouse qualifier; to simulate a mouse connected@{ub}
       This switch is similar to IGNOREMOUSE but instead of ignoring this
       special relative_mouse flag it simply sets it for all keypresses
       that are let through AllKeys. This makes all other hotkey programs,
       such as ToolsDaemon, that also have problems to work as well.
  
     @{b}Ignore CapsLock for configured keys; make them useful also with CapsLock on@{ub}
       Use this switch if you would like to be able to use your hotkeys
       also when CapsLock is on.
  
     @{b}Flush the upstroke of configured keys; to eat also the release of keys@{ub}
       Normally you only want to use the keypress, not the release of the
       key as a hotkey. But to be able to bypass the screenblanker also
       the upstroke (release of the key) must be used and eaten. Using
       this switch takes care of this automatically and matches and flushes
       the upstroke key as well even if you only use the downstroke.

       Note: This switch is pretty useless without EAT or EATALL.

     @{b}Add qualifiers to USB extended multimedia keys.@{ub}

     @{b}Do not warn about suspicious wheel codes.@{ub}


   @{u}The input window for learning a new key.@{uu}

     This is where key codes are recorded. Already recorded hotkeys are disabled
     when this window is open to allow you to freely press any key.

     @{b}Use code@{ub}
       Select and use the currently marked code and close the window.
  
     @{b}Clear list@{ub}
       Clears the list.

     @{b}Stop@{ub}
       Stop input to the list. Useful if you need to scroll it to pick a key
       further up. The button changes into Continue which you can press to
       continue key input.

     @{b}Cancel@{ub}
       Abort the learning process and close the window.

     @{b}No mouse@{ub}
       When in learn mode it may be useful to disable mouse clicks otherwise
       it can be hard to select the last key for usage.

     @{b}No upstrokes@{ub}
       Use this switch to disable key upstokes. Normally you don't need to use
       upstrokes as hotkeys and it is therefore good to disable them from the
       output to make it easier to read and pick your key.


   @{u}If you hate GUIs: Here is a step-by-step guide which should make it easy@{uu}
   @{u}enough to set up AllKeys using CLI if you follow it.@{uu}

     @{b}1.@{ub} Start a text editor.
  
     @{b}2.@{ub} Enter the special first line with any global parameters you
        may like to use. Leave it empty if necessary.
  
     @{b}3.@{ub} Open a shell.
  
     @{b}4.@{ub} Start AllKeys from the shell with the LEARN/S parameter:
        "AllKeys learn"
        You may also use the NOUPSTROKES or NOMOUSE switches to filter out
        the release of keys and mouse clicks from the shell output.
  
     @{b}5.@{ub} Press a key you want to use, f.ex. Play. (Not all keys work.)
        (You can also use qualifiers like Shift+Play, use the last number
        outputted in such a case as each keypress will output numbers.)
        Note that character keys, such as letters, will block the shell
        until you press Enter if you type the letters in the same shell
        you started AllKeys.
  
     @{b}6.@{ub} You will see a line such as this:
        "CODE=$80000073 CLASS=RAWKEY"
  
     @{b}7.@{ub} Type or copy'n'paste this line on a new line in the text
        editor. (When you mess around in the text editor the shell will
        output a lot more numbers, ignore these.)
  
     @{b}8.@{ub} You can use the EAT switch here on the same line if you would
        like this key to be eaten by AllKeys, i.e. not set to the rest of the
        system.
        If you like all keys to be eaten it is easier to use the EATALL switch
        in the first line instead.
  
     @{b}9.@{ub} You can also enter TRANSLATE=<$code to translate to>[,CLASS] if
        you wish to translate the code. Do not forget EAT (or EATALL) if
        don't wish the original code to be sent aswell.
  
     @{b}10.@{ub} If you like to execute an arexx command for the key you specify RXPORT
         and RXCOMMAND here.
  
     @{b}11.@{ub} Write COMMAND=<your commandline> as the last thing on the line
         to execute a command for the key. It is not necessary to have a command.
  
         If you want the same key to execute more than one command you can just
         use the same key code many times with different commands attached to them.
         Note that keyrepeat codes are not the same as the codes for immediately
         pressed keys.
  
     @{b}12.@{ub} Repeat steps 5 to 11 until you have gathered all your keys.
  
     @{b}13.@{ub} You should now have a text file containing one line for each key.
         (See below for sample files.)
  
     @{b}14.@{ub} Press Ctrl+C in the shell to terminate AllKeys.
  
     @{b}15.@{ub} Save the text file as "ENVARC:AllKeys.prefs".
  
     @{b}16.@{ub} Start AllKeys without any argument and try out your keys!
  
     @{b}17.@{ub} If everything is OK you can put "Run >NIL: AllKeys" in you
         S:user-startup to be sure to always have access to your keys.


   @{u}Sample of an AllKeys.prefs file:@{uu}
     PRI=85 FLUSHUPSTROKES
     CODE=$8000e020 CLASS=XKEY EAT RXPORT=AMIGAAMP RXCOMMAND=PAUSE
     CODE=$80000073 EAT RXPORT=AMIGAAMP RXCOMMAND PLAY ;This is a comment
     CODE=$80000076 EAT RXPORT=AMIGAAMP RXCOMMAND PREVIOUS
     CODE=$80000077 EAT RXPORT=AMIGAAMP RXCOMMAND NEXT
     CODE=$c000007e CLASS=MOUSE TRANSLATE $80800034,RAWKEY ;Paste with the mouse
     CODE=$8000006D COMMAND=WBRun Internet:IBrowse/IBrowse
     CODE=$8001006E COMMAND=run >NIL: rx Rexx:MP3-sleep.rexx
     CODE=$80000047 TRANSLATE=$8000005F

   The command can be anything you can write in a normal shell including
   redirection (>, <) and arguments. Note that commands are executed
   synchronously so you probably want to put "Run >NIL: " or "WBRun "
   infront of programs that does not exit immediately or they will
   block AllKeys from processing more keys until this program has exited.

   The lines may end with a ;comment if you like. An entire line can
   also be a comment if it starts with ";". It is also possible to have
   blank lines in the prefs file. Just make sure they are really empty,
   no spaces or such.


@endnode

@node news "News.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}News and Changes
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} Added a switch to allow multimedia keys on USB keyboards to work with
           qualifiers such that for example Shift + Play can do something different
           than Play alone.

   @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} Fixed multimedia key names for USB keyboards.

   @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} Added up and down buttons so you can reorder your key commands in the list.

 @{b}v2.31
 ~~~~~@{ub}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a crash that happened if you would add an Arexx command without
           a port and executed this command.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Replaced the obsoleted Execute() with SystemTagList() for executing
           commands.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Removed the MorphOS version. It serves little purpose anymore
           since it doesn't have a GUI and MorphOS have similar tools build-in already.

 @{b}v2.3
 ~~~~@{ub}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added support for different Sub Classes. This makes some USB keyboards
     work better, and perhaps other pointer devices.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The input priority and task priority where mixed so the task pri
     was always set to the same as the input pri.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed an error in the prefs file which made it impossible to use
     "Flush upstrokes .." together with the "Do not warn .." flag.

 @{b}v2.2
 ~~~~@{ub}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a problem with the ARexx command being split between the
     ARexx command and CLI command fields. To fix this I enforced
     the non-use of "double quotes" in the ARexx command.

 @{b}v2.1
 ~~~~~@{ub}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} AllKeys crashed on OS4 Final if it didn't recognized a key.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Upstrokes did show as the key that was released, but as a hex number.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a wierd problem with the listbrowser not reporting inline edit
     quick enough. Strange...?

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed the error-messages that popped up when trying to edit the command
     or translate field in the GUI.

 @{b}v2.0
 ~~~~~@{ub}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Finally a GUI!
     Sorry MOS users, but it became a ReAction GUI...
     Reason: Not quite sure, but I think I came to the conclusion
     that AllKeys is not much more useful on MOS than any other
     hotkey tool due to the lack of XKEYs, and it was easy to copy
     the GUI and everything underneath it from Macc which was already
     using ReAction.
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} AllKeys is a commodity featuring everything, except its own hotkey ;)
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Translating into WHEEL events was not possible at all.
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} If another program, such as Macc, added or removed input-events
     in the chain that was put in there by AllKeys during translate it
     caused a crash.
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The prefs is now read from ENV: to make it possible to differentiate
     between Save and Use, and the ability to have a Cancel button.
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a learn-raw-mode (GUI only) that makes it possible to see all
     input-events (except timer-ticks) that flows in the input-stream.
     This mode could perhaps be useful if you have a device that AllKeys
     can't read in the normal learn-mode.

 @{b}v1.3
 ~~~~~@{ub}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added support for a second scroll-wheel. Untested though.
     If you have set some actions on the wheel, you need to re-learn
     the codes as they are slightly different now to give room for
     codes from the second wheel too.
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now AllKeys has a notify on the prefs file which means that you
     can edit the prefs and as soon as you save the file your new
     setting will instantly be available!
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now the TRANSLATE option makes a copy of the trigger code and
     sends both the original key and the translated code to the
     input queue, unless you has EAT(ALL) of course. Then only the
     translated code will be sent as usual.
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} It is possible to translate the same key into many different
     codes. Add one line for every new translation.
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added the global flag IGNORECAPSLOCK. If this is used it doesn't
     matter if capslock is on or not, the hotkeys will work anyway,
     which is not the case without this flag.
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} AllKeys now automatically cancels the numpad qualifier from the
     mouse events MOUSE and WHEEL. This eliminates the peculiar
     side-effect that the mouse hotkeys stopped working if something
     had just been typed on the numpad on the keyboard. Now the mouse
     commands will always be usable even if the numpad has just been used.
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Better error handling and messages when errors are encountered
     in the prefs file. Previously, most errors were silently ignored.
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} It is now possible to have blank lines, and lines that are just a
     ;comment in the prefs file. To comment out a line just put a
     semi-colon (;) infront of it. Having a semi-colon-comment at the
     end of lines has always been possible with the newstyle template.
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed the TRANSLATE option so that it now uses RAWKEY as default.
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Included my own prefs file as an example. I have a Logitech
     Cordless Desktop MX.
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Updated the MorphOS version. It should now be up to speed also.
     MorphOS doesn't have XKEYs though so don't expect any such
     from this version.
     If you use MorphOS you should click the "I use MorphOS" icon
     before anything else. If you regret yourself you can just click
     the "I use AmigaOS4" icon afterwards :)
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Updated the documentation. It was not 100% correct for v1.2.
   
   @{fg fill}* OLD *@{fg text} Still no GUI, but there will be one in the next version.
     It will most likely be MUI to be compatible with MOS.
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Included a fixed ActivateWindow that shouldn't crash sporadically
     anymore.

 @{b}v1.2
 ~~~~~@{ub}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Recompiled to work with OS4 Update 4.
     It probably won't work on update 3 and below any more.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Full support for all multimedia-keys!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Possibility to read the mouse buttons, all of them!
     Only my 8th mousebutton can not be read.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added support for sending arexx commands directly.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now using NewLib which made the exe A LOT smaller!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Removed oldstyle support which means that you need to apply
     the template for all lines if you have not done that already.

 @{b}v1.1
 ~~~~~@{ub}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a TRANSLATE option to the lines so that you can use
     AllKeys to translate keys aswell. It cannot translate qualifiers
     though, like translate Ctrl to Left Amiga and then use Ctrl as a
     Left Amiga qualifier key for hotkeys doesn't work for example.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added IGNOREMOUSE and SETMOUSE as global switches. These are useful
     if you have a wireless optical mouse that needs recharging in
     between. I you reboot without having access to a real mouse, most
     hotkeys will stop working because the Realitive_Mouse flag will
     not be set in input.device. These flags can make the hotkeys ignore
     this flag, or force this flag on every key passed through input.device
     for use by other hotkey-based programs that also stop working when
     there is no mouse.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a MOS version.

 @{b}v1.0
 ~~~~~@{ub}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now AllKeys is OS4 native. One less emulated input-handler in the
     system :-)

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added some functionality to the prefs file.
     Now it is possible to specify that a key gets eaten by AllKeys
     making it possible to use the keys without deactivating a
     screen blanker for example.

 @{b}v0.1
 ~~~~~@{ub}

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Initial release for Classic 68k.


@endnode

@node bugs "Bugs.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Bugs
  ~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   * Probably doesn't work on OS4 upd3 and below anymore due to a change
     in the API for upd4.

   * AllKeys can't handle multiple inputevents that are linked, such as
     what the UTF-8 tool and AllKeys itself sends when using TRANSLATE.

   Please @{"report" link auth} if you find any other bugs!


@endnode

